{"title_page": "Casimir Gide", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n | name             = Casimir Gide \n | image            = Three Grces -Charles Challon.JPG\n | imagesize        = \n | caption          = ''Les Trois Gr\u00e2ces'' by Charles Challon for ''Le Diable boiteux'' by Casimir Gide\n | birth_name       = \n | birth_date       = 4 July 1804\n | birth_place      = [[Paris]]\n | death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1868|02|18|1804|07|04}}\n | death_place      =\n | othername   =     \n | occupation  = Composer, bookseller, prints editor \n | years_active     = \n | spouse           = \n | signature        = \n}}\n\n'''Casimir Gide''' (4 July 1804 \u2013 18 February 1868) was a 19th-century French composer, bookseller as well as prints and maps editor.\n\n==Biography==\nThe son of the Parisian bookseller Theophile Etienne Gide (1768\u20131837), to whom he would succeed, and of a singer in the chapel of the king, he studied [[harmony]] and [[musical composition]] at the [[Conservatoire de Paris]]. On 4 February 1833, he received the bookseller patent from the Maison Gide fils. He was a major printer of [[Lithography|lithographs]] and financed the publication of six volumes, among them nineteen of the ''Voyages pittoresques et romantiques dans l'ancienne France'' by [[Charles Nodier]] and [[Justin Taylor]].<ref>[[Jean-Michel Leniaud]], B\u00e9atrice Bouvier, ''Le Livre d'architecture, XVe\u2013XXe si\u00e8cle'' (2002), p. 41.</ref> In 1854, he was one of the first to launch the trend of salon operettas and artistic evenings.<ref>Vapereau, ''Dictionnaire universel des contemporains'', p. 744.</ref>\n\n==Works==\nHe wrote [[incidental music]], [[ballet]]s and [[opera]]s.\n\n===Shows===\n*1828: ''Les Trois Marie'', [[vaudeville]] by [[Louis Duport]], chant and accompagnement\n*1829: ''La [[Cachucha]]''\n*1830: ''La Chatte blanche''\n*1830: ''Les Trois Catherine'', with [[Adolphe Adam]]\n*1830: ''Le Roi de Sicile'', [[op\u00e9ra comique]] in 1 act, with [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Souli\u00e9]]\n*1831: ''Les Jumeaux de la R\u00e9ole''\n*1832: ''[[La tentation]]''\n*1835: ''L'\u00cele des pirates''\n*1836: ''[[Le Diable boiteux (ballet)|Le Diable boiteux]]'', ballet pantomime in 3 acts, with [[Edmond Burat de Gurgy]] and [[Fanny Elssler]]\n*1838: ''La Voli\u00e8re ou les Oiseaux de Boccace''\n*1839: ''[[La Tarentule]]'', ballet-pantomime\n*1847: ''Oza\u00ef'', ballet pantomime in 2 acts, with [[Jean Coralli]]\n* ''Pas redoubl\u00e9 pour harmonie militaire''\n* ''Romance'' (with Horace Gide)\n*1858: ''Belphegor''\n\n===Piano music===\n* ''Quadrille et valse'' (piano) for ''Le Diable boiteux''\n* ''rondos-fantaisies'' on ''Oza\u00ef''\n* ''Trois quadrilles de contredanses suivis de deux valses et un galop'' on ''La Tentation'' (with [[Fromental Hal\u00e9vy]])\n\n==Libretti==\n*1834: ''L'Ang\u00e9lus'', op\u00e9ra comique in 1 act (with [[Jean-Joseph Ader]])\n*1845: ''Fragment d'un r\u00e9p\u00e9titeur de ballet''\n* ''Le Cam\u00e9lia'', petite ronde pour piano sur une valse du ballet, ''Le Diable boiteux'', Op. 102\n* ''Le Muguet'', petit rondo pour piano sur un air de danse du ballet, ''Le Diable boiteux''\n* ''La Tentation'', [[opera]] in 5 acts, lyrics by Cav\u00e9, music by Hal\u00e9vy, ballets music by Gide\n\n==Lithographic prints==\n*1845: ''Ch\u00e2teau de Dompierre''\n*1845: ''Grande Salle de l'H\u00f4tel de Ville de St Quentin''\n*1845: ''Int\u00e9rieur de l'\u00c9glise de Notre Dame de Nesle''\n*1857: ''Ancien H\u00f4tel de Ville de Ch\u00e2lons-sur-Marne''\n*1857: ''Ancienne \u00c9glise St Nicaise \u00e0 Reims''\n*1857: ''\u00c9glise d'Hermouville''\n*1857: ''\u00c9glise St Laurent \u00e0 Nogent sur Seine''\n*1857: ''Portail du Sud de l'\u00c9glise de M\u00e9zi\u00e8res''\n*1857: ''Portail m\u00e9ridional de l'\u00c9glise de R\u00e9thel''\n*1857: ''Vues d'une partie de l'\u00c9glise de Bourgogne''\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zck5AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA744&dq=%22Gide+Casimir%22+1804&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=OWWbU-qnF4K30QXm6YHoCA&ved=0CCgQuwUwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Gide%20Casimir%22%201804&f=false [[Gustave Vapereau]], ''Dictionnaire universel des contemporains'', 1865, (p.&nbsp;744)]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=2kMQAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA3&dq=%22Gide+Casimir%22+1804&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=uGabU6r1GcfB0QWD4YGoAg&ved=0CEkQuwUwCDgK#v=onepage&q=%22Gide%20Casimir%22%201804&f=false [[Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph F\u00e9tis]], ''Biographie universelle des musiciens'', 1869, (p.&nbsp;3)] <!-- primary source [[:fr:template:plume]] -->\n* George Grove, John Alexander Fuller-Maitland, ''Grove's Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', vol.2, 1906, (p.&nbsp;273)\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Dumesnil]], ''La musique romantique fran\u00e7aise'', 1944, (p.&nbsp;140)\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=JoEpuVk_H9QC&pg=PT71&lpg=PT71&dq=Casimir+Gide+1804+1868&source=bl&ots=anWhQAutHS&sig=u7r3QbAiR6dEJEY2Hzy0f4bUvQA&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=8lybU82RGayT0QXy-4DADQ&ved=0CDUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Casimir%20Gide%201804%201868&f=false Eug\u00e8ne de Montalembert, [[Claude Abromont]], ''Guide des genres de la musique occidentale'']\n* Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Robert, ''La Musique fran\u00e7aise au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', 1970, (p.&nbsp;41)\n* [[Carl Dahlhaus]], [[Sieghart D\u00f6hring]], ''Pipers Enzyklop\u00e4die des Musiktheaters'', 1997, {{p.|370}})\n* Jean-Louis Tamvaco, Ivor Forbes Guest, ''Les cancans de l'Op\u00e9ra'', 2000, (p.&nbsp;994)\n* Jean-Jacques Velly, ''Le dessous des notes'', 2001, (p.&nbsp;73) <!-- primary source [[:fr:template:plume]] -->\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=kOar3-OQw2IC&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=%22Casimir+Gide%22+1804+1868&source=bl&ots=ooduUziP9h&sig=8Rn8hWV4xINCJ3CGnV9-fGByetM&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=H2CbU__5B6yT0QXy-4DADQ&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Casimir%20Gide%22%201804%201868&f=false William E. Studwell, ''Minor Ballet Composers'', 2012, (p.&nbsp;43)] <!-- primary source [[:fr:template:plume]] -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b8420288n Buste de Casimir Gide sur Gallica]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gide, Casimir}}\n[[Category:1804 births]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:French ballet composers]]\n[[Category:French booksellers]]\n[[Category:French publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:French Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n | name             = Casimir Gide \n | image            = Three Grces -Charles Challon.JPG\n | imagesize        = \n | caption          = ''Les Trois Gr\u00e2ces'' by Charles Challon for ''Le Diable boiteux'' by Casimir Gide\n | birth_name       = \n | birth_date       = 4 July 1804\n | birth_place      = [[Paris]]\n | death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1868|02|18|1804|07|04}}\n | death_place      =\n | othername   =     \n | occupation  = Composer, bookseller, prints editor \n | years_active     = \n | spouse           = \n | signature        = \n}}\n\n'''Casimir Gide''' (4 July 1804 \u2013 18 February 1868) was a 19th-century French composer, bookseller as well as prints and maps editor.\n\n== Biography ==\nThe son of the Parisian bookseller Theophile Etienne Gide (1768-1837), to whom he will succeed and of a singer in the chapel of the king, he studied [[harmony]] and [[musical composition]] at the [[Conservatoire de Paris]]. On 4 February 1833, he was patended bookseller from maison Gide fils. He was a major printer of [[Lithography|lithographs]] and financed the publication of six volumes among the nineteen of the ''Voyages pittoresques et romantiques dans l'ancienne France'' by [[Charles Nodier]] and [[Justin Taylor]].<ref>[[Jean-Michel Leniaud]], B\u00e9atrice Bouvier, ''Le livre d'architecture, XVe\u2013XXe si\u00e8cle'', 2002, {{p.|41}}</ref> In 1854, he was one of the first to launch the trend of salon operettas and artistic evenings.<ref>Vapereau, ''Dictionnaire universel des contemporains'', {{p.|744}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nHe wrote [[incidental music]], [[ballet]]s and [[opera]]s.\n\n=== Shows ===\n*1828: ''Les Trois Marie'', [[vaudeville]] by [[Louis Duport]], chant and accompagnement\n*1829: ''La [[Cachucha]]''\n*1830: ''La Chatte blanche''\n*1830: ''Les Trois Catherine'', with [[Adolphe Adam]]\n*1830: ''Le Roi de Sicile'', [[op\u00e9ra comique]] in 1 act, with [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Souli\u00e9]]\n*1831: ''Les Jumeaux de la R\u00e9ole''\n*1832: ''[[La tentation]]''\n*1835: ''L'\u00cele des pirates''\n*1836: ''[[Le Diable boiteux (ballet)|Le Diable boiteux]]'', ballet pantomime in 3 acts, with [[Edmond Burat de Gurgy]] and [[Fanny Elssler]]\n*1838: ''La Voli\u00e8re ou les Oiseaux de Boccace''\n*1839: ''[[La Tarentule]]'', ballet-pantomime\n*1847: ''Oza\u00ef'', ballet pantomime in 2 acts, with [[Jean Coralli]]\n* ''Pas redoubl\u00e9 pour harmonie militaire''\n* ''Romance !'' (with Horace Gide)\n*1858: ''Belphegor''\n\n=== Musics ===\n* ''Quadrille et valse'' (piano) for ''Le Diable boiteux''\n* ''rondos-fantaisies'' on ''Oza\u00ef''\n* ''Trois quadrilles de contredanses suivis de deux valses et un galop'' on ''La Tentation'' (with [[Fromental Hal\u00e9vy]])\n\n== Texts ==\n*1834: ''L'Ang\u00e9lus'', [[op\u00e9ra comique]] in 1 act (with [[Jean-Joseph Ader]])\n*1845: ''Fragment d'un r\u00e9p\u00e9titeur de ballet''\n* ''Le Cam\u00e9lia'' (petite ronde pour piano sur une valse du ballet ''Le Diable boiteux''). op. 102\n* ''Le muguet'' (petit rondo pour piano sur un air de danse du ballet ''Le Diable boiteux''\n* ''La Tentation'', [[opera]] in 5 acts, lyrics by Cav\u00e9, music by Hal\u00e9vy, ballets music by Gide (morceaux d\u00e9tach\u00e9s chant et piano by Gide)\n\n=== Lithography prints ===\n*1845: ''Ch\u00e2teau de Dompierre''\n*1845: ''Grande Salle de l'H\u00f4tel de Ville de St Quentin''\n*1845: ''Int\u00e9rieur de l'\u00c9glise de Notre Dame de Nesle''\n*1857: ''Ancien H\u00f4tel de Ville de Ch\u00e2lons-sur-Marne''\n*1857: ''Ancienne \u00c9glise St Nicaise \u00e0 Reims''\n*1857: ''\u00c9glise d'Hermouville''\n*1857: ''\u00c9glise St Laurent \u00e0 Nogent sur Seine''\n*1857: ''Portail du Sud de l'\u00c9glise de M\u00e9zi\u00e8res''\n*1857: ''Portail m\u00e9ridional de l'\u00c9glise de R\u00e9thel''\n*1857: ''Vues d'une partie de l'\u00c9glise de Bourgogne''\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zck5AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA744&dq=%22Gide+Casimir%22+1804&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=OWWbU-qnF4K30QXm6YHoCA&ved=0CCgQuwUwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Gide%20Casimir%22%201804&f=false [[Gustave Vapereau]], ''Dictionnaire universel des contemporains'', 1865, (p.&nbsp;744)]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=2kMQAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA3&dq=%22Gide+Casimir%22+1804&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=uGabU6r1GcfB0QWD4YGoAg&ved=0CEkQuwUwCDgK#v=onepage&q=%22Gide%20Casimir%22%201804&f=false [[Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph F\u00e9tis]], ''Biographie universelle des musiciens'', 1869, (p.&nbsp;3)] <!-- primary source [[:fr:template:plume]] -->\n* George Grove, John Alexander Fuller-Maitland, ''Grove's Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', vol.2, 1906, (p.&nbsp;273)\n* [[Ren\u00e9 Dumesnil]], ''La musique romantique fran\u00e7aise'', 1944, (p.&nbsp;140)\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=JoEpuVk_H9QC&pg=PT71&lpg=PT71&dq=Casimir+Gide+1804+1868&source=bl&ots=anWhQAutHS&sig=u7r3QbAiR6dEJEY2Hzy0f4bUvQA&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=8lybU82RGayT0QXy-4DADQ&ved=0CDUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Casimir%20Gide%201804%201868&f=false Eug\u00e8ne de Montalembert, [[Claude Abromont]], ''Guide des genres de la musique occidentale'']\n* Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Robert, ''La Musique fran\u00e7aise au XIXe si\u00e8cle'', 1970, (p.&nbsp;41)\n* [[Carl Dahlhaus]], [[Sieghart D\u00f6hring]], ''Pipers Enzyklop\u00e4die des Musiktheaters'', 1997, {{p.|370}})\n* Jean-Louis Tamvaco, Ivor Forbes Guest, ''Les cancans de l'Op\u00e9ra'', 2000, (p.&nbsp;994)\n* Jean-Jacques Velly, ''Le dessous des notes'', 2001, (p.&nbsp;73) <!-- primary source [[:fr:template:plume]] -->\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=kOar3-OQw2IC&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=%22Casimir+Gide%22+1804+1868&source=bl&ots=ooduUziP9h&sig=8Rn8hWV4xINCJ3CGnV9-fGByetM&hl=fr&sa=X&ei=H2CbU__5B6yT0QXy-4DADQ&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Casimir%20Gide%22%201804%201868&f=false William E. Studwell, ''Minor Ballet Composers'', 2012, (p.&nbsp;43)] <!-- primary source [[:fr:template:plume]] -->\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b8420288n Buste de Casimir Gide sur Gallica]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gide, Casimir}}\n[[Category:French Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:French ballet composers]]\n[[Category:French booksellers]]\n[[Category:French publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:1804 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Aklein62", "label": "safe", "comment": "Some formal edits.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Casimir_Gide"}
