002\u201303 NFL playoffs|2002]] !! IND\n | 1 || 1 || 3 || 17 || 5.7 || 7 || 0 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2003\u201304 NFL playoffs|2003]] !! IND\n | 3 || 3 || 15 || 172 || 11.5 || 20 || 2 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2004\u201305 NFL playoffs|2004]] !! IND\n | 2 || 2 || 13 || 256 || 19.7 || 49 || 2 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || 1 || 1\n|-\n ! [[2005\u201306 NFL playoffs|2005]] !! IND\n | 1 || 1 || 7 || 97 || 13.9 || 24 || 0 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs|2006]] !! IND\n | 4 || 4 || 17 || 216 || 12.7 || 53 || 2 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2007\u201308 NFL playoffs|2007]] !! IND\n | 1 || 1 || 7 || 76 || 10.9 || 21 || 1 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2008\u201309 NFL playoffs|2008]] !! IND\n | 1 || 1 || 4 || 129 || 32.2 || 72 || 1 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2009\u201310 NFL playoffs|2009]] !! IND\n | 3 || 3 || 16 || 164 || 10.2 || 25 || 1 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || 1 || 0\n|-\n ! [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs|2010]] !! IND\n | 1 || 1 || 1 || 1 || 1.0 || 1 || 0 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2012\u201313 NFL playoffs|2012]] !! IND\n | 1 || 1 || 9 || 114 || 12.7 || 20 || 0 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n ! [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs|2014]] !! IND\n | 3 || 3 || 1 || 12 || 12.0 || 12 || 0 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n! colspan=2|Career\n! 21 || 21 || 93 || 1,254 || 13.5 || 72 || 9 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || 2 || 1\n|}\n\n==Post-playing career==\n[[File:ReggieWayneHonor.jpeg|thumb|Wayne in November 2018, after being inducted into the Colts' Ring of Honor.]]\nOn April 30, 2018, the Colts announced that Wayne would join the team as a volunteer receivers coach.<ref>http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000930496/article/colts-name-reggie-wayne-volunteer-receivers-coach</ref> On November 18, 2018, Wayne became the 15th player to be inducted into the team's [[Indianapolis Colts Ring of Honor|Ring of Honor]], in a ceremony attended by former teammates including Marvin Harrison, Manning and Saturday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2018/11/18/reggie-wayne-thanks-fans-colts-irsay-he-joins-ring-honor/2049251002/|title=Reggie Wayne thanks fans, Colts, Irsay as he joins Ring of Honor|website=[[IndyStar]]|date=November 18, 2018|first=Jim|last= Ayello|accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> On January 2, 2020, Wayne was named one of 15 modern-era finalists for election into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio. He and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] safety [[Troy Polamalu]] are the only two finalists for 2020 to be nominated in their first year of eligibility. The Hall of Fame selection was made on February 1, 2020, the day before Super Bowl LIV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Polamalu, Wayne lead football Hall of Fame finalists in 1st year of eligibility|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nfl/polamalu-wayne-lead-football-hall-of-fame-finalists-in-1st-year-of-eligibility/ar-BBYyM5l?ocid=sf|access-date=January 2, 2020|website=msn.com|date=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.reggiewayne.com Official website]\n* [http://www.patriots.com/team/players/roster/reggie-wayne New England Patriots bio]\n* [http://www.colts.com/team/roster/Reggie-Wayne/a394623a-9a60-46b5-ad7a-4867d1c2028e Indianapolis Colts bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120312035202/http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/wayne_reggie00.html Miami Hurricanes bio]\n* {{espn nfl|id=2578|name=Reggie Wayne}}\n* {{Footballstats |pfr=WaynRe00}}\n\n{{2001 NFL Draft}}\n{{ColtsFirstPick}}\n{{Super Bowl XLI}}\n{{Indianapolis Colts Ring of Honor}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wayne, Reggie}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:John Ehret High School alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Colts players]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football players]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:People from Southwest Ranches, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|name=Reggie Wayne\n|image=Reggie Wayne.JPG\n|image_size=230\n|alt=\n|caption=Wayne with the Colts in September 2010\n|number=87\n|position=[[Wide receiver]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1978|11|17|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[New Orleans, Louisiana]]\n|high_school=[[John Ehret High School|John Ehret]] ([[Marrero, Louisiana]])\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=0\n|weight_lbs=203\n|college=[[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami (FL)]]\n|draftyear=2001\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=30\n|pastteams=\n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] ({{NFL Year|2001}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}}\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLI|XLI]])\n* 6\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2007 Pro Bowl|2006]]\u2013[[2011 Pro Bowl|2010]], [[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2010 All-Pro Team|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2007 All-Pro Team|2007]], [[2009 All-Pro Team|2009]])\n* [[List of National Football League season receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (2007)\n* [[Indianapolis Colts Ring of Honor]]\n* All-[[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]]\n|statlabel1=[[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1=1,070\n|statlabel2=[[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue2=14,345\n|statlabel3=[[Average|Receiving average]]\n|statvalue3=13.4\n|statlabel4=[[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue4=82\n|nflnew=reggiewayne/2504747\n}}\n\n'''Reginald Wayne''' (born November 17, 1978) is a former [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] who spent his entire 14-year career with the [[Indianapolis Colts]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami]], and was drafted by the Colts in the first round (30th overall) of the [[2001 NFL Draft]]. A six-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection, Wayne was a member of the Colts' [[Super Bowl XLI]] championship team that beat the [[Chicago Bears]]. He ranks tenth all-time in NFL career receptions,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_career.htm |accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref> tenth all-time in [[List of National Football League receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_career.htm|title=NFL career receiving yardage leaders|publisher=NFL Pro Reference.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> and 23rd all-time in [[List of National Football League receiving touchdowns leaders|career touchdown receptions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_td_career.htm|title=NFL career receiving touchdown leaders|publisher=NFL Pro Reference.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref> On December 14, 2014, Wayne played in both his 209th game and his 142nd win as a member of the Colts, breaking the franchise records set by [[Peyton Manning]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/indianapolis-colts-reggie-wayne-breaks-franchise-record-for-most-games-played-121414|title=Colts' Reggie Wayne breaks franchise record for games played|work=foxsports.com|date=December 14, 2014|accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWayne is the youngest of three sons. His father, Ralph, is a former linebacker for [[Grambling State Tigers football|Grambling State]]. A [[New Orleans Saints]] fan in his youth, he was more interested in [[baseball]] growing up but chose football by the time he attended [[John Ehret High School]].<ref>{{citenews|title=No Place Like Home|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1998-09-03/sports/9809020737_1_ehret-reggie-wayne-wayne-s-life|publisher=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|date=September 3, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{citenews|title=Reggie Wayne would love for New Orleans Saints to win Super Bowl, but not this one|url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2010/02/reggie_wayne_would_love_for_ne.html|publisher=[[The Times-Picayune]]|date=February 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nWayne attended the [[University of Miami]], where he was a four-year starter for the [[Miami Hurricanes football|Hurricanes]]. He set a school record of 173 career catches (including 36 consecutive games with a reception) and is one of only five wide receivers in school history to post 20 or more touchdowns in his career, along with [[Michael Irvin]], [[Lamar Thomas]], [[Leonard Hankerson]] and [[Andre Johnson]]. Wayne's 48 receptions during the 1997 season set a school record for freshmen, which still stands today. Wayne also ran [[track and field]] at the [[University of Miami]], where he recorded a personal best of 21.87 seconds in the [[200 meters]]. Wayne graduated with a degree in liberal arts; his roommate was [[Baltimore Ravens]] safety [[Ed Reed]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Colts.com|url=http://www.colts.com/sub.cfm?page=bio&player_id=67|title=Reggie Wayne: The Official Website of the Indianapolis Colts|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061022111131/http://www.colts.com/sub.cfm?page=bio&player_id=67|archivedate=October 22, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=Football \u2013 Bio: Reggie Wayne|url=http://www.hurricanesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=28700&ATCLID=205558824|publisher=[[Miami Hurricanes|hurricanesports.com]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821044100/http://www.hurricanesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=28700&ATCLID=205558824|archivedate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n'''College statistics'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|- align=center\n|Year\t||Team\t||G\t||GS\t||Rec\t||Yards\t||AVG\t||TD\n|- align=center\n|1997 \t||MIA \t||11 \t||10 \t||48 \t||640 \t||13.3 \t||2\n|- align=center\n|1998 \t||MIA \t||9\t||9 \t||42 \t||629 \t||15.0 \t||4\n|- align=center\n|1999 \t||MIA\t||12\t||12\t||40\t||486\t||12.1\t||4\n|- align=center\n|2000 \t||MIA \t||11 \t||11 \t||43 \t||755 \t||17.5\t||10\n|- align=center\n|Total \t||N/A \t||43\t||42 \t||173 \t||2,510 ||14.3 \t||20\n|}\n\nWayne was inducted into the University of Miami Sports Hall of Fame at their 43rd Annual Induction Banquet held on March 24, 2011.<ref>{{citenews|title=Morgan, Moss and Wayne headline UM Hall of Fame Class of '11|url=http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/sports/w-track/spec-rel/110210aaa.html|date=November 2, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120708183807/http://hurricanesports.cstv.com/sports/w-track/spec-rel/110210aaa.html|archivedate=July 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Indianapolis Colts===\nWayne was selected by the [[Indianapolis Colts]] with the 30th selection in the [[2001 NFL Draft]], the sixth of 34 wide receivers taken in a draft class that included eight future pro-bowlers at the position. He was expected to eventually complement the Colts' other star receiver, [[Marvin Harrison]]. He played all 211 games of his career for the Colts.<ref name=glog />\n\n====2001 season====\n[[File:Reggie Nelson Reggie Wayne MNF.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Wayne playing against the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] on October 22, 2007.]]\nIn Wayne's first year, he caught 27 passes for 345 yards with no touchdowns.  He only made nine starts and missed three games altogether due to a high ankle sprain. \n\n====2002 season====\nHis yards doubled the next year as he caught 49 passes for 716 yards and four touchdowns. He had at least one reception in 14 of the team's 16 games, and more than 100 yards receiving in three of them.<ref name=glog />\n\n====2003 season====\nWayne broke into the starting lineup in the 2003 season, and he caught 68 balls for 838 yards and seven touchdowns. This included two different games with 141 yards receiving. \n\n====2004 season====\nIn 2004, Wayne caught 77 passes for 1,210 yards and 12 touchdowns during a season in which Colts quarterback [[Peyton Manning]] threw a then-record 49 touchdowns. He had four 100+ yard games, including personal-bests 184 yards on 11 receptions in Week 3 against [[2003 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay]]. During the playoffs, Wayne was named the \"[[Wild card (sports)#National Football League|Wild Card]] Weekend Offensive Player of the Week\" after the Colts beat the [[Denver Broncos|Broncos]]. Wayne had 10 receptions for 221 yards and two touchdowns in the game,<ref name=glog >[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/W/WaynRe00/gamelog/ Reggie Wayne game log, PFR]</ref> then the second-most receiving yards in a wild card game.<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=game&year_min=1950&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=P&playoff_round=w&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=rec_yds&c1comp=gt&c1val=200&c5val=1.0&order_by=pass_td 200+ receiving yards in wild card games], PFR. At the time, Wayne was second only to [[Eric Moulds]] (240 in the 1998 postseason), but has since been passed by teammate [[T.Y. Hilton]] (224 in 2013).</ref>\n\n====2005 season====\nIn 2005, Wayne again had 1,000+ yards receiving, and increased his reception total to 83. In Week 17, the 13-2 Colts rested most of their top players in preparation for the playoffs, and Wayne had zero receptions for the last time in his remaining 134 regular season games.<ref name=glog /> In the playoffs, Wayne had 97 yards, a two-point conversion, and a critical 22-yard reception to set up a potential game-tying field goal in an 21-18 loss to the eventual champion [[2005 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200601150clt.htm Colts v Steelers, Division Round, Box Score]</ref>\n\n====2006 season====\nIn 2006, Wayne signed a 6-year, $39.5 million contract.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=2340118 Colts re-sign WR Wayne, likely won't tag James]</ref> He broke the 100-yard mark five times, including a season-best 134 yards and three touchdowns in Week 8 against [[2006 Denver Broncos season|Denver]].<ref name=glog /> He went on to catch 86 balls for a then-career-high 1,310 yards and 9 touchdowns. As a result, Wayne was selected to his first [[Pro Bowl]]. In the postseason, Wayne had five receptions in each of the first three games, then helped the Colts defeat the [[Chicago Bears]] in [[Super Bowl XLI]] with a 53-yard touchdown reception in the first quarter.\n\n====2007 season====\nIn 2007, Wayne responded to a rash of injuries on the team, including Harrison and tight end [[Dallas Clark]], by setting a then-career-high in receptions (104), and a career-high in yards (1,510). This included six games with over 100 yards receiving, and a season-best 168 yards with a touchdown in Week 8 against [[2007 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina]].<ref name=glog /> He led the league in receiving yards and was selected to go to the Pro Bowl for the second consecutive year.\n\n====2008 season====\nIn 2008, Wayne posted a Pro Bowl season for the third consecutive year with 82 catches for 1,145 yards and six touchdowns. This included four 100+ yard games, four touchdowns in the first five games, and a 65-yard score on the opening drive of Week 10 against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref name=glog /> In the Wild Card round, he had 129 yards including a 72-yard touchdown, but the Colts lost in overtime, eliminated in the first round by the [[San Diego Chargers]] for the second consecutive year.\n\n====2009 season====\nIn Week 10 of 2009, Wayne caught the winning touchdown pass with 0:14 left against the [[New England Patriots]] in what is now known as the \"4th and 2\" game.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009111512/2009/REG10/patriots@colts#menu=gameinfo%7CcontentId%3A09000d5d8143b6c2&tab=videos Highlights of 4th and 2 game], nfl.com</ref> Wayne was also selected as a starter for the [[Pro Bowl]], but couldn't play due to the Colts playing in the Super Bowl. In [[Super Bowl XLIV]], Wayne had 5 catches for 46 yards, but the Colts lost to the [[New Orleans Saints]] 31-17.\n[[File:Reggie Wayne 2010.jpg|thumb|Wayne playing against the Philadelphia Eagles during the 2010 season.]]\n\n====2010 season====\nIn 2010, Wayne was second in the NFL receptions with 111 (a career-high), and third in receiving yards with 1,355. During a season where the Colts heavily relied on [[Peyton Manning]] to win games, Wayne again cemented himself as one of the top receivers in the NFL. This included a franchise-record 15 receptions which he converted into 196 yards against [[2010 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville]] in Week 4, and 14 receptions for 200 yards in Week 13 against [[2010 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas]]. Wayne was also selected as a starter the [[Pro Bowl]].\n\n====2011 season====\nWayne's numbers were lower than usual in 2011 without Peyton Manning starting at quarterback, though he still led team in receptions (75) and receiving yards (960). He had four touchdown receptions as well. On September 25, 2011, Wayne recorded his 800th catch against the Pittsburgh Steelers.\n\n====2012 season====\nOn March 13, 2012, the Colts re-signed Wayne to a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20120313/SPORTS03/120313030/Reggie-Wayne-returns-Colts-Garcon-joins-Redskins?odyssey=nav%7Chead|title=Reggie Wayne re-signs as Colts confront free agency|accessdate=March 14, 2012|newspaper=Indianapolis Star}}</ref> Before the 2012 Week 5 matchup with the [[Green Bay Packers]], the news of head coach [[Chuck Pagano]]'s leukemia surfaced. Wayne's history with Pagano goes back to his college years, where Pagano was the Hurricanes' defensive backs coach, and Pagano's hiring as the Colts' head coach was a large factor in Wayne's decision to re-sign with Indianapolis.  In response, Wayne caught 13 passes for a career-high 212 receiving yards and a game-winning touchdown from rookie quarterback [[Andrew Luck]]; Wayne earned the AFC Offensive Player of the Week award due to his performance, the first of his career. In Week 12 against [[Buffalo Bills]], Wayne broke [[Cris Carter]]'s record of consecutive games with 3 or more receptions with 59 games.  He also passed former [[Washington Redskins]] receiver [[Art Monk]] for 12th on the NFL's all-time receptions list during the first half.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000100205/article/reggie-wayne-sets-nfl-consecutive-multicatch-games-record Reggie Wayne Sets NFL Consecutive Multicatch Games Record]</ref> During the [[2012-13 NFL Playoffs|wild-card game]] against the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Wayne had 114 yards on nine receptions and moved into second in career playoff catches with 92 \u2014 only 59 behind leader [[Jerry Rice]]. However, the Colts lost the game 24-9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130106/SPORTS01/130106032/NFL-playoffs-Ray-Lewis-Ravens-beat-Colts-Seahawks-win-RGIII-reinjures-knee |title=NFL playoffs: Ray Lewis, Ravens beat Colts; Seahawks win as RGIII reinjures knee\n|publisher=Detroit Free Press|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nWayne was selected as the wide receiver for USA Football\u2019s 2012 [http://usafootball.com/all-fundamentals-team All-Fundamentals Team], which honors 26 NFL players each year for executing the fundamentals of their position.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://usafootball.com/news/featured-articles/26-nfl-players-named-usa-footballs-2012-all-fundamentals-team|title=26 NFL Players named to USA Football's 2012 All-Fundamentals Team |publisher=usafootball.com|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref> \n\n====2013 season====\nIn 2013, Wayne again posted 100 yards against [[2013 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville]] in Week 4. In a Week 8 loss to [[2013 San Diego Chargers|San Diego]], Wayne became the ninth player to reach 1,000 career receptions. However, a week later, Wayne [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|tore his ACL]]; it was announced the next day that he would miss the remainder of the 2013 season. The injury also ended his consecutive games played streak at 189, the third-longest for a wide receiver in NFL history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9858289/reggie-wayne-indianapolis-colts-season|title=Source: Reggie Wayne tears ACL|work=ESPN.com|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\nWith the retirement of [[Tony Gonzalez]], 36-year-old Wayne entered 2014 as the active leader in career receiving yards. He gained 98 more in a season-opening loss to [[2014 Denver Broncos season|Denver]], and 119 in Week 4 against Tennessee. In Week 8, Wayne became the ninth receiver in NFL history to record 14,000 receiving yards.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/wayne-leads-list-colts-players-getting-mris-205433835--nfl.html|title=Wayne leads list of Colts players getting MRIs|work=sports.yahoo.com|date=October 20, 2014|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> He suffered an elbow injury in the game and missed the following week's matchup against the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/11755110/reggie-wayne-indianapolis-colts-play-vs-pittsburgh-steelers|title=Reggie Wayne out for Colts|work=espn.go.com|date=October 24, 2014|accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref> Near the conclusion of the Colts' 2014 season, it was announced that Wayne had played with a torn triceps since Week 6, which would require an offseason surgery to repair.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000449093/article/reggie-wayne-needs-offseason-triceps-surgery|title=Reggie Wayne needs offseason triceps surgery|last=Wesseling|first=Chris|work=NFL.com|date=December 24, 2014|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref> He had just one reception in the Colts' three post-season games, concluding his career with franchise records for postseason receptions (93); receiving yards, yards-from-scrimmage, and all-purpose yards (1,254), receiving and total touchdowns (9), games with at least one touchdown (8), and games with 100+ yards receiving (3, shared with [[Dallas Clark]] and [[T.Y. Hilton]]).<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=combined&year_min=1950&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=P&team_id=clt&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=rec_yds&c1comp=gt&c1val=100&c5val=1.0&order_by=rec_yds Colts postseason receiving leaders, PFR]</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2015, the Colts announced that they would not re-sign Wayne, which made him a free agent on March 10.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000476869/article/colts-announce-they-will-not-resign-reggie-wayne|title=Colts announce they will not re-sign Reggie Wayne|last=Orr|first=Conor|work=NFL.com|date=March 6, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Retirement====\n[[File:WaynePatriots.jpg|thumb|right|Wayne at Patriots practice in August 2015]]\nOn August 24, 2015, Wayne signed a one-year contract with the [[New England Patriots]] worth up to $3 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/08/24/report-patriots-sign-reggie-wayne/|title=Report: Patriots sign Reggie Wayne|last=Alper|first=Josh|date=August 24, 2015|work=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots, veteran WR Reggie Wayne agree to one-year deal|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/13501199/reggie-wayne-new-england-patriots-agree-deal|website=ESPN.com|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> On September 5, 2015, Wayne requested and was granted his release from the Patriots.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots release 11 players; Place Brandon LaFell on PUP|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608214355/http://www.patriots.com/news/2015/09/05/patriots-release-11-players-place-brandon-lafell-pup|website=Patriots.com|date=September 5, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2016, after not playing the entire [[2015 NFL season|2015 season]], Wayne announced his retirement from professional football, saying, \"It was fun, but it's time. It's just time. Whenever you can admit that you're done, you know you're done.\"<ref>http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14580425/veteran-wr-reggie-wayne-says-just-retire?ex_cid=sportscenterTW&sf18987374=1</ref> He finished his NFL career seventh all-time in career receptions, eighth all-time in [[List of National Football League receiving yards leaders|receiving yards]] and 23rd in [[List of National Football League receiving touchdowns leaders|career touchdown receptions]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_career.htm|title=NFL career receptions leaders|publisher=NFL Pro Reference.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_yds_career.htm|title=NFL career receiving yardage leaders|publisher=NFL Pro Reference.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/rec_td_career.htm|title=NFL career receiving touchdown leaders|publisher=NFL Pro Reference.com|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"t